In TypeScript, you can use a type assertion to tell the type system that you know that a value has a specific type, even if the type system may have a different understanding of the value's type. Here's an example:

```typescript
const value: string | number = "hello";

// In this case, the type system knows that "value" can be either a string or a number.
// If you try to access a property or method that only exists on strings, the compiler will complain.
console.log(value.length); // Error: Property 'length' does not exist on type 'string | number'.

// To tell the type system that you know that "value" is a string, you can use a type assertion like this:
const strLength = (value as string).length; // The type assertion tells the type system to treat "value" as a string for this expression.
console.log(strLength); // No error, because "value" is treated as a string for the expression.
```

In this example, the variable "value" is initialized with a value of type "string | number". This means that the type system knows that "value" can be either a string or a number, but it doesn't know which one it is. If you try to access a property or method that only exists on strings, the compiler will complain because it doesn't know if "value" is actually a string.

To tell the type system that you know that "value" is a string, you can use a type assertion like (value as string). This tells the type system to treat "value" as a string for the expression following the type assertion. In this case, we are accessing the "length" property of "value", which only exists on strings, so we use the type assertion to tell the type system that we know it's safe to access this property.

Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Declare variables
    string word;
    int count = 0;
    ifstream file("file.txt");
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        cout << "File could not be opened." << endl;
        return 1;
    }
    // Read the word from the user and store it in the word variable
    cout << "Enter the word to search for: ";
    getline(cin, word);
    // Read each line of the file
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
        // Check if the current line contains the word we are looking for
        if (line.find(word) != string::npos) {
            // Increment the count variable by 1 for each occurrence of the word in the current line
            count++;
        }
    }
    // Close the file stream
    file.close();
    // Print the number of occurrences of the word in the file to the console. 
    cout << "The word '" << word << "' was found " << count << " times in the file." << endl;    
}
